Fix for the problem is to modify `StreamReaderAdapter` in `hbmqtt/adapters.py`.


	class StreamReaderAdapter(ReaderAdapter):
	    """
	    Asyncio Streams API protocol adapter
	    This adapter relies on StreamReader to read from a TCP socket.
	    Because API is very close, this class is trivial
	    """
	    def __init__(self, reader: StreamReader):
		self._reader = reader

	    @asyncio.coroutine
	    def read(self, n=-1) -> bytes:
		if n == -1:
		    data = yield from self._reader.read(n)
		else:
		    data = yield from self._reader.readexactly(n)
		return data

	    def feed_eof(self):
		return self._reader.feed_eof()

The `read` method is enforcing reading exact number of bytes as requested by parameter `n` using `readexactly` method.

It seems as if `asyncio` implements StreamReader in such a way, that `.read(n)` does not guarrantee delivering given number of bytes resulting in some cases in shorter responses. This a bit surprising behaviour confused decoding input stream and incompletely read data was used to decode topic name from it, leaving remaining bytes for for topic data.

I will provide pull request with this fix.

Thanks to @rhorenov for helping me in pair programming to resolve this issue. It was fun.

Agreed, but I think the point that was raised during the Web API design was to have _homogenous_ objects.

Allowing the suggested shortcut would give up inhomogenous inputs (and possibly outputs) such as:

```JSON
"birth": "1987-04-01",
"salary": {
    "2017-01": 2000
}
```

I think the main way of dealing with `ETERNITY ` defined variable was imagined to be more like that:

```JSON
"birth": {
    "ETERNITY": "1987-04-01"
},
"salary": {
    "2017-01": 2000
}
```

which is less "absurd", more semantic but... heavy and not really intuitive.

In practice, users such as mes-aides just put a random month instead of explicitly using the "ETERNITY" key, because it gives the same result, and is probably less work on their side.

