@jamesls It looks good. I like keeping the amount of properties we expose small for now (i.e. just `message` and `subject`). It should work fine for the use case I was thinking. As for the `topic_name` parameter, will that be the parameter we use for managed resources? For [on_s3_event](https://github.com/aws/chalice/issues/855#issuecomment-394207579), it looks like we decided to name it `bucket` so we can potentially overload it with a managed resource when needed. Do we want to do the same for topics? The one downside in naming the parameter `topic` is that it is not obvious if you want the name or arn of the topic.


@BigChief45 No the `app.lambda_function` would no longer be needed. So if you take this pure lambda function that was hooked up to an SNS topic out of band of a `chalice deploy`:
```python
@app.lambda_function()
def handle_sns_message(event, context):
    message = json.loads(event['Records'][0]['Sns']['Message'])
    # Do something with this message
```
It could be translated to this:
```python
@app.on_sns_message(topic_name='my-topic')
def handle_sns_message(event):
    message = json.loads(event.message)
    # Do something with this message
```
Plus chalice will set up the lambda subscription to SNS and permissions for you. So you would not need to do it out of band of `chalice deploy`.

As to the `context`, I would assume it would not be exposed on the `event` object that gets passed in to start. However, we could expose the `context` as a property of the `event` object that gets passed in, if we want to in the future. But it sounds like it is not targeted for this initial launch. Feel free to chime in on if you think we should include it for the initial launch though.

