I added this issuse from my phone.
here are some more details and the procedure to reproduce the error:
Nginx settings before running the script:
server {
    include /etc/nginx/subextensions/*;
    server_name www.duckgamer.com;
    server_name duckgamer.com;
    root $Websites/duckgamer;

    location / {

        }
}

, after running the script(in arch linux with default setup of pacman -S letsencrypt letsencrypt-nginx):
letsencrypt -d duckgamer.com -d www.duckgamer.com --standalone
in the easy/secure window, selected:
secure make all requests reditect to secure HTTPS access
new nginx config:
server {

    if ($scheme != "https") {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    }
    ssl_stapling_verify on;
    ssl_stapling on;
    ssl_trusted_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/duckgamer.com/chain.pem;
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/duckgamer.com/privkey.pem;
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/duckgamer.com/fullchain.pem;
    error_log /var/lib/letsencrypt/error.log;
    access_log /var/lib/letsencrypt/access.log;
    listen 443 ssl;
    include /etc/nginx/subextensions/*;
    server_name www.duckgamer.com;
    server_name duckgamer.com;
    root $Websites/duckgamer;

    location / {
    }
}

The problem in this config is the combination of:
 if ($scheme != "https") {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    }

with:
 listen 443 ssl;
HTTP requests never reach this server block because of the listen 443 ssl.
rendering the HTTP protocol entirely inaccesible.

suggested fix:
Instead of putting
if ($scheme != "https") {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    }
inside the same block
you should put the whole redirect in its own SERVER block here is my approach:

server {
    ssl_stapling_verify on;
    ssl_stapling on;
    ssl_trusted_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/duckgamer.com/chain.pem;
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/duckgamer.com/privkey.pem;
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/duckgamer.com/fullchain.pem;
    error_log /var/lib/letsencrypt/error.log;
    access_log /var/lib/letsencrypt/access.log;
    listen 443 ssl;
    include /etc/nginx/subextensions/*;
    server_name www.duckgamer.com;
    server_name duckgamer.com;
    root $Websites/duckgamer;
    location / {
    }
}

server{
    server_name www.duckgamer.com;
    server_name duckgamer.com;
  return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

this is both, a working + the recommended approach since "ifs" are evil by the NGINX recommendations.
https://www.nginx.com/resources/wiki/start/topics/depth/ifisevil/

